# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mips-assembly
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language usually has one statement per machine code instruction (1:1), but constants, comments, assembler directives, symbolic labels of, e.g., memory locations, registers, and macros are generally also supported.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The first assembly code in which a language is used to represent machine code instructions is found in Kathleen and Andrew Donald Booth's 1947 work, *Coding for A.R.C.*.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly code is converted into executable machine code by a utility program referred to as an *assembler*.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The term "assembler" is generally attributed to Wilkes, Wheeler and Gill in their 1951 book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer*, who, however, used the term to mean "a program that assembles another program consisting of several sections into a single program".
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The conversion process is referred to as *assembly*, as in *assembling* the source code.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The computational step when an assembler is processing a program is called *assembly time*.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Because assembly depends on the machine code instructions, each assembly language is specific to a particular computer architecture such as x86 or ARM.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Sometimes there is more than one assembler for the same architecture, and sometimes an assembler is specific to an operating system or to particular operating systems.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Most assembly languages do not provide specific syntax for operating system calls, and most assembly languages can be used universally with any operating system, as the language provides access to all the real capabilities of the processor, upon which all system call mechanisms ultimately rest.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In contrast to assembly languages, most high-level programming languages are generally portable across multiple architectures but require interpreting or compiling, much more complicated tasks than assembling.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In the first decades of computing, it was commonplace for both systems programming and application programming to take place entirely in assembly language.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] While still irreplaceable for some purposes, the majority of programming is now conducted in higher-level interpreted and compiled languages.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In "No Silver Bullet", Fred Brooks summarised the effects of the switch away from assembly language programming: "Surely the most powerful stroke for software productivity, reliability, and simplicity has been the progressive use of high-level languages for programming.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Today, it is typical to use small amounts of assembly language code within larger systems implemented in a higher-level language, for performance reasons or to interact directly with hardware in ways unsupported by the higher-level language.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For instance, just under 2% of version 4.9 of the Linux kernel source code is written in assembly; more than 97% is written in C.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language uses mnemonic symbols to represent low-level machine instructions (opcodes), directives, and usually architectural registers and flags.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some of the mnemonics may be built-in and some user-defined.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Many operations require one or more operands in order to form a complete instruction.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Most assemblers permit named constants, registers, and labels for program and memory locations, and can calculate expressions for operands.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Thus, programmers are freed from tedious repetitive calculations and assembler programs are much more readable than machine code.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Depending on the architecture, these elements may also be combined for specific instructions or addressing modes using offsets or other data as well as fixed addresses.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Many assemblers offer additional mechanisms to facilitate program development, to control the assembly process, and to aid debugging.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some are column oriented, with specific fields in specific columns; this was very common for machines using punched cards in the 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers have free-form syntax, with fields separated by delimiters, e.g., punctuation, white space.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers are hybrid, with, e.g., labels, in a specific column and other fields separated by delimiters; this became more common than column-oriented syntax in the 1960s.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] An **assembler** program creates object code by translating combinations of mnemonics and syntax for operations and addressing modes into their numerical equivalents.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This representation typically includes an *operation code* ("opcode") as well as other control bits and data.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The assembler also calculates constant expressions and resolves symbolic names for memory locations and other entities.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The use of symbolic references is a key feature of assemblers, saving tedious calculations and manual address updates after program modifications.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Most assemblers also include macro facilities for performing textual substitution – e.g., to generate common short sequences of instructions as inline, instead of *called* subroutines.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers may also be able to perform some simple types of instruction set-specific optimizations.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] One concrete example of this may be the ubiquitous x86 assemblers from various vendors.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Called jump-sizing, most of them are able to perform jump-instruction replacements (long jumps replaced by short or relative jumps) in any number of passes, on request.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Others may even do simple rearrangement or insertion of instructions, such as some assemblers for RISC architectures that can help optimize a sensible instruction scheduling to exploit the CPU pipeline as efficiently as possible.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assemblers have been available since the 1950s, as the first step above machine language and before high-level programming languages such as Fortran, Algol, COBOL and Lisp.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There have also been several classes of translators and semi-automatic code generators with properties similar to both assembly and high-level languages, with Speedcode as perhaps one of the better-known examples.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There may be several assemblers with different syntax for a particular CPU or instruction set architecture.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For instance, an instruction to add memory data to a register in a x86-family processor might be `add eax,[ebx]`, in original *Intel syntax*, whereas this would be written `addl (%ebx),%eax` in the *AT&T syntax* used by the GNU Assembler.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Despite different appearances, different syntactic forms generally generate the same numeric machine code.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] A single assembler may also have different modes in order to support variations in syntactic forms as well as their exact semantic interpretations (such as FASM-syntax, TASM-syntax, ideal mode, etc., in the special case of x86 assembly programming).
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There are two types of assemblers based on how many passes through the source are needed (how many times the assembler reads the source) to produce the object file.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In both cases, the assembler must be able to determine the size of each instruction on the initial passes in order to calculate the addresses of subsequent symbols.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In an assembler with peephole optimization, addresses may be recalculated between passes to allow replacing pessimistic code with code tailored to the exact distance from the target.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The original reason for the use of one-pass assemblers was memory size and speed of assembly – often a second pass would require storing the symbol table in memory (to handle forward references), rewinding and rereading the program source on tape, or rereading a deck of cards or punched paper tape.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Later computers with much larger memories (especially disc storage), had the space to perform all necessary processing without such re-reading.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The advantage of the multi-pass assembler is that the absence of errata makes the linking process (or the program load if the assembler directly produces executable code) faster.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] See Language design below for more details.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] A program written in assembly language consists of a series of mnemonic processor instructions and meta-statements (known variously as declarative operations, directives, pseudo-instructions, pseudo-operations and pseudo-ops), comments and data.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language instructions usually consist of an opcode mnemonic followed by an operand, which might be a list of data, arguments or parameters.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some instructions may be "implied", which means the data upon which the instruction operates is implicitly defined by the instruction itself—such an instruction does not take an operand.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The resulting statement is translated by an assembler into machine language instructions that can be loaded into memory and executed.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For example, the instruction below tells an x86/IA-32 processor to move an immediate 8-bit value into a register.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The binary code for this instruction is 10110 followed by a 3-bit identifier for which register to use.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The identifier for the *AL* register is 000, so the following machine code loads the *AL* register with the data 01100001.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This binary computer code can be made more human-readable by expressing it in hexadecimal as follows.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Here, `B0` means "Move a copy of the following value into *AL*", and `61` is a hexadecimal representation of the value 01100001, which is 97 in decimal.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language for the 8086 family provides the mnemonic MOV (an abbreviation of *move*) for instructions such as this, so the machine code above can be written as follows in assembly language, complete with an explanatory comment if required, after the semicolon.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This is much easier to read and to remember.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Other assemblers may use separate opcode mnemonics such as L for "move memory to register", ST for "move register to memory", LR for "move register to register", MVI for "move immediate operand to memory", etc.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] If the same mnemonic is used for different instructions, that means that the mnemonic corresponds to several different binary instruction codes, excluding data (e.g. the `61h` in this example), depending on the operands that follow the mnemonic.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For example, for the x86/IA-32 CPUs, the Intel assembly language syntax `MOV AL, AH` represents an instruction that moves the contents of register *AH* into register *AL*.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The first byte, 88h, identifies a move between a byte-sized register and either another register or memory, and the second byte, E0h, is encoded (with three bit-fields) to specify that both operands are registers, the source is *AH*, and the destination is *AL*.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In a case like this where the same mnemonic can represent more than one binary instruction, the assembler determines which instruction to generate by examining the operands.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In the first example, the operand `61h` is a valid hexadecimal numeric constant and is not a valid register name, so only the `B0` instruction can be applicable.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In the second example, the operand `AH` is a valid register name and not a valid numeric constant (hexadecimal, decimal, octal, or binary), so only the `88` instruction can be applicable.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly languages are always designed so that this sort of lack of ambiguity is universally enforced by their syntax.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For example, in the Intel x86 assembly language, a hexadecimal constant must start with a numeral digit, so that the hexadecimal number 'A' (equal to decimal ten) would be written as `0Ah` or `0AH`, not `AH`, specifically so that it cannot appear to be the name of register *AH*.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Returning to the original example, while the x86 opcode 10110000 (`B0`) copies an 8-bit value into the *AL* register, 10110001 (`B1`) moves it into *CL* and 10110010 (`B2`) does so into *DL*.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language examples for these follow.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The syntax of MOV can also be more complex as the following examples show.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In each case, the MOV mnemonic is translated directly into one of the opcodes 88-8C, 8E, A0-A3, B0-BF, C6 or C7 by an assembler, and the programmer normally does not have to know or remember which.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] An assembler transforms assembly language into machine code, and the reverse can at least partially be achieved by a disassembler.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Unlike high-level languages, there is a one-to-one correspondence between many simple assembly statements and machine language instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] However, in some cases, an assembler may provide *pseudoinstructions* (essentially macros) which expand into several machine language instructions to provide commonly needed functionality.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For example, for a machine that lacks a "branch if greater or equal" instruction, an assembler may provide a pseudoinstruction that expands to the machine's "set if less than" and "branch if zero (on the result of the set instruction)".
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Most full-featured assemblers also provide a rich macro language (discussed below) which is used by vendors and programmers to generate more complex code and data sequences.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Likewise, since comments in the assembly language source file are ignored by the assembler and have no effect on the object code it generates, a disassembler is always completely unable to recover source comments.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Each computer architecture has its own machine language.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Computers differ in the number and type of operations they support, in the different sizes and numbers of registers, and in the representations of data in storage.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] While most general-purpose computers are able to carry out essentially the same functionality, the ways they do so differ; the corresponding assembly languages reflect these differences.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Multiple sets of mnemonics or assembly-language syntax may exist for a single instruction set, typically instantiated in different assembler programs.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In these cases, the most popular one is usually that supplied by the CPU manufacturer and used in its documentation.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Two examples of CPUs that have two different sets of mnemonics are the Intel 8080 family and the Intel 8086/8088.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Because Intel claimed copyright on its assembly language mnemonics (on each page of their documentation published in the 1970s and early 1980s, at least), some companies that independently produced CPUs compatible with Intel instruction sets invented their own mnemonics.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The Zilog Z80 CPU, an enhancement of the Intel 8080A, supports all the 8080A instructions plus many more; Zilog invented an entirely new assembly language, not only for the new instructions but also for all of the 8080A instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For example, where Intel uses the mnemonics *MOV*, *MVI*, *LDA*, *STA*, *LXI*, *LDAX*, *STAX*, *LHLD*, and *SHLD* for various data transfer instructions, the Z80 assembly language uses the mnemonic *LD* for all of them.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] A similar case is the NEC V20 and V30 CPUs, enhanced copies of the Intel 8086 and 8088, respectively.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Like Zilog with the Z80, NEC invented new mnemonics for all of the 8086 and 8088 instructions, to avoid accusations of infringement of Intel's copyright.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] "Hello, world!" can be printed using 32-bit assembly language for an x86 processor with little help from an operating system.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] "Call outchr" calls some mechanism that prints a character in AL to the console.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] A non zero-length string must be terminated with a byte of zero.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There is a large degree of diversity in the way the authors of assemblers categorize statements and in the nomenclature that they use.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In particular, some describe anything other than a machine mnemonic or extended mnemonic as a pseudo-operation (pseudo-op).
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Instructions (statements) in assembly language are generally very simple, unlike those in high-level languages.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Generally, a mnemonic is a symbolic name for a single executable machine language instruction (an opcode), and there is at least one opcode mnemonic defined for each machine language instruction.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Each instruction typically consists of an *operation* or *opcode* plus zero or more *operands*.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Most instructions refer to a single value or a pair of values.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Operands can be immediate (value coded in the instruction itself), registers specified in the instruction or implied, or the addresses of data located elsewhere in storage.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This is determined by the underlying processor architecture: the assembler merely reflects how this architecture works.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] *Extended mnemonics* are often used to specify a combination of an opcode with a specific operand, e.g., the System/360 assemblers use `B` as an extended mnemonic for `BC` with a mask of 15 and `NOP` ("NO OPeration" – do nothing for one step) for `BC` with a mask of 0.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers also support simple built-in macro-instructions that generate two or more machine instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For instance, with some Z80 assemblers the instruction `ld hl,bc` is recognized to generate `ld l,c` followed by `ld h,b`.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] These are sometimes known as *pseudo-opcodes*.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Mnemonics are arbitrary symbols; in 1985 the IEEE published Standard 694 for a uniform set of mnemonics to be used by all assemblers.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There are instructions used to define data elements to hold data and variables.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] They define the type of data, the length and the alignment of data.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] These instructions can also define whether the data is available to outside programs (programs assembled separately) or only to the program in which the data section is defined.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers classify these as pseudo-ops.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly directives, also called pseudo-opcodes, pseudo-operations or pseudo-ops, are commands given to an assembler "directing it to perform operations other than assembling instructions".
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Directives affect how the assembler operates and "may affect the object code, the symbol table, the listing file, and the values of internal assembler parameters".
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Sometimes the term *pseudo-opcode* is reserved for directives that generate object code, such as those that generate data.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The names of pseudo-ops often start with a dot to distinguish them from machine instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Pseudo-ops can make the assembly of the program dependent on parameters input by a programmer, so that one program can be assembled in different ways, perhaps for different applications.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Or, a pseudo-op can be used to manipulate presentation of a program to make it easier to read and maintain.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Another common use of pseudo-ops is to reserve storage areas for run-time data and optionally initialize their contents to known values.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Symbolic assemblers let programmers associate arbitrary names (*labels* or *symbols*) with memory locations and various constants.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Usually, every constant and variable is given a name so instructions can reference those locations by name, thus promoting self-documenting code.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In executable code, the name of each subroutine is associated with its entry point, so any calls to a subroutine can use its name.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Inside subroutines, GOTO destinations are given labels.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers support *local symbols* which are often lexically distinct from normal symbols (e.g., the use of "10$" as a GOTO destination).
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers, such as NASM, provide flexible symbol management, letting programmers manage different namespaces, automatically calculate offsets within data structures, and assign labels that refer to literal values or the result of simple computations performed by the assembler.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Labels can also be used to initialize constants and variables with relocatable addresses.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly languages, like most other computer languages, allow comments to be added to program source code that will be ignored during assembly.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Judicious commenting is essential in assembly language programs, as the meaning and purpose of a sequence of binary machine instructions can be difficult to determine.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The "raw" (uncommented) assembly language generated by compilers or disassemblers is quite difficult to read when changes must be made.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Many assemblers support *predefined macros*, and others support *programmer-defined* (and repeatedly re-definable) macros involving sequences of text lines in which variables and constants are embedded.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The macro definition is most commonly a mixture of assembler statements, e.g., directives, symbolic machine instructions, and templates for assembler statements.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This sequence of text lines may include opcodes or directives.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Once a macro has been defined its name may be used in place of a mnemonic.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] When the assembler processes such a statement, it replaces the statement with the text lines associated with that macro, then processes them as if they existed in the source code file (including, in some assemblers, expansion of any macros existing in the replacement text).
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Macros in this sense date to IBM autocoders of the 1950s.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In assembly language, the term "macro" represents a more comprehensive concept than it does in some other contexts, such as the pre-processor in the C programming language, where its #define directive typically is used to create short single line macros.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembler macro instructions, like macros in PL/I and some other languages, can be lengthy "programs" by themselves, executed by interpretation by the assembler during assembly.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Since macros can have 'short' names but expand to several or indeed many lines of code, they can be used to make assembly language programs appear to be far shorter, requiring fewer lines of source code, as with higher level languages.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] They can also be used to add higher levels of structure to assembly programs, optionally introduce embedded debugging code via parameters and other similar features.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Macro assemblers often allow macros to take parameters.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Thus a macro might generate numerous assembly language instructions or data definitions, based on the macro arguments.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This could be used to generate record-style data structures or "unrolled" loops, for example, or could generate entire algorithms based on complex parameters.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For instance, a "sort" macro could accept the specification of a complex sort key and generate code crafted for that specific key, not needing the run-time tests that would be required for a general procedure interpreting the specification.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] An organization using assembly language that has been heavily extended using such a macro suite can be considered to be working in a higher-level language since such programmers are not working with a computer's lowest-level conceptual elements.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Underlining this point, macros were used to implement an early virtual machine in SNOBOL4 (1967), which was written in the SNOBOL Implementation Language (SIL), an assembly language for a virtual machine.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The target machine would translate this to its native code using a macro assembler.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This allowed a high degree of portability for the time.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Macros were used to customize large scale software systems for specific customers in the mainframe era and were also used by customer personnel to satisfy their employers' needs by making specific versions of manufacturer operating systems.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] IBM OS/360 uses macros to perform system generation.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The user specifies options by coding a series of assembler macros.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembling these macros generates a job stream to build the system, including job control language and utility control statements.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This is because, as was realized in the 1960s, the concept of "macro processing" is independent of the concept of "assembly", the former being in modern terms more word processing, text processing, than generating object code.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The concept of macro processing appeared, and appears, in the C programming language, which supports "preprocessor instructions" to set variables, and make conditional tests on their values.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Unlike certain previous macro processors inside assemblers, the C preprocessor is not Turing-complete because it lacks the ability to either loop or "go to", the latter allowing programs to loop.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Despite the power of macro processing, it fell into disuse in many high level languages (major exceptions being C, C++ and PL/I) while remaining a perennial for assemblers.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Macro parameter substitution is strictly by name: at macro processing time, the value of a parameter is textually substituted for its name.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The most famous class of bugs resulting was the use of a parameter that itself was an expression and not a simple name when the macro writer expected a name.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] the intention was that the caller would provide the name of a variable, and the "global" variable or constant b would be used to multiply "a".
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] If foo is called with the parameter `a-c`, the macro expansion of `load a-c*b` occurs.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] To avoid any possible ambiguity, users of macro processors can parenthesize formal parameters inside macro definitions, or callers can parenthesize the input parameters.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Packages of macros have been written providing structured programming elements to encode execution flow.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The earliest example of this approach was in the Concept-14 macro set, originally proposed by Harlan Mills (March 1970), and implemented by Marvin Kessler at IBM's Federal Systems Division, which provided IF/ELSE/ENDIF and similar control flow blocks for OS/360 assembler programs.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This was a way to reduce or eliminate the use of GOTO operations in assembly code, one of the main factors causing spaghetti code in assembly language.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This approach was widely accepted in the early 1980s (the latter days of large-scale assembly language use).
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] IBM's High Level Assembler Toolkit includes such a macro package.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Another design was A-Natural, a "stream-oriented" assembler for 8080/Z80 processors from Whitesmiths Ltd.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] (developers of the Unix-like Idris operating system, and what was reported to be the first commercial C compiler).
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The language was classified as an assembler because it worked with raw machine elements such as opcodes, registers, and memory references; but it incorporated an expression syntax to indicate execution order.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Parentheses and other special symbols, along with block-oriented structured programming constructs, controlled the sequence of the generated instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] A-natural was built as the object language of a C compiler, rather than for hand-coding, but its logical syntax won some fans.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There has been little apparent demand for more sophisticated assemblers since the decline of large-scale assembly language development.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In spite of that, they are still being developed and applied in cases where resource constraints or peculiarities in the target system's architecture prevent the effective use of higher-level languages.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] When the stored-program computer was introduced, programs were written in machine code, and loaded into the computer from punched paper tape or toggled directly into memory from console switches.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] In late 1948, the Electronic Delay Storage Automatic Calculator (EDSAC) had an assembler (named "initial orders") integrated into its bootstrap program.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] It used one-letter mnemonics developed by David Wheeler, who is credited by the IEEE Computer Society as the creator of the first "assembler".
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Reports on the EDSAC introduced the term "assembly" for the process of combining fields into an instruction word.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] SOAP (Symbolic Optimal Assembly Program) was an assembly language for the IBM 650 computer written by Stan Poley in 1955.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Assembly languages eliminated much of the error-prone, tedious, and time-consuming first-generation programming needed with the earliest computers, freeing programmers from tedium such as remembering numeric codes and calculating addresses.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] They were once widely used for all sorts of programming.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] By the late 1950s their use had largely been supplanted by higher-level languages in the search for improved programming productivity.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Today, assembly language is still used for direct hardware manipulation, access to specialized processor instructions, or to address critical performance issues.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Typical uses are device drivers, low-level embedded systems, and real-time systems (see § Current usage).
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Numerous programs were written entirely in assembly language.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] The Burroughs MCP (1961) was the first computer for which an operating system was not developed entirely in assembly language; it was written in Executive Systems Problem Oriented Language (ESPOL), an Algol dialect.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Many commercial applications were written in assembly language as well, including a large amount of the IBM mainframe software developed by large corporations.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] COBOL, FORTRAN and some PL/I eventually displaced assembly language, although a number of large organizations retained assembly-language application infrastructures well into the 1990s.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language was the primary development language for 8-bit home computers such as the Apple II, Atari 8-bit computers, ZX Spectrum, and Commodore 64.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Interpreted BASIC on these systems did not offer maximum execution speed and full use of facilities to take full advantage of the available hardware.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language was the default choice for programming 8-bit consoles such as the Atari 2600 and Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Key software for IBM PC compatibles such as MS-DOS, Turbo Pascal, and the Lotus 1-2-3 spreadsheet was written in assembly language.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] As computer speed grew exponentially, assembly language became a tool for speeding up parts of programs, such as the rendering of *Doom*, rather than a dominant development language.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] In the 1990s, assembly language was used to maximise performance from systems such as the Sega Saturn, and as the primary language for arcade hardware using the TMS34010 integrated CPU/GPU such as *Mortal Kombat* and *NBA Jam*.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] There has been debate over the usefulness and performance of assembly language relative to high-level languages.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Although assembly language has specific niche uses where it is important (see below), there are other tools for optimization.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] As of July 2017, the TIOBE index of programming language popularity ranks assembly language at 11, ahead of Visual Basic, for example.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Assembler can be used to optimize for speed or optimize for size.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] In the case of speed optimization, modern optimizing compilers are claimed to render high-level languages into code that can run as fast as hand-written assembly, despite some counter-examples.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] The complexity of modern processors and memory sub-systems makes effective optimization increasingly difficult for compilers and assembly programmers alike.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Increasing processor performance has meant that most CPUs sit idle most of the time, with delays caused by predictable bottlenecks such as cache misses, I/O operations and paging, making raw code execution speed a non-issue for many programmers.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language is still taught in most computer science and electronic engineering programs.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Although few programmers today regularly work with assembly language as a tool, the underlying concepts remain important.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Such fundamental topics as binary arithmetic, memory allocation, stack processing, character set encoding, interrupt processing, and compiler design would be hard to study in detail without a grasp of how a computer operates at the hardware level.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Since a computer's behaviour is fundamentally defined by its instruction set, the logical way to learn such concepts is to study an assembly language.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Most modern computers have similar instruction sets.
[src:mips-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Therefore, studying a single assembly language is sufficient to learn the basic concepts, recognize situations where the use of assembly language might be appropriate, and to see how efficient executable code can be created from high-level languages.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] An **instruction set architecture** (**ISA**) is an abstract model that defines the programmable interface of the CPU of a computer, defining how software interacts with hardware.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] CPU) that interprets instructions described by an ISA is an implementation of that ISA.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Generally, the same ISA is used for a family of related CPU devices.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] In general, an ISA defines the instructions, data types, registers, and the programming interface for managing main memory such as addressing modes, virtual memory, and memory consistency mechanisms.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] The ISA also includes the input/output model of the programmable interface.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] An ISA specifies the behavior implied by machine code running on an implementation of that ISA in a fashion that does not depend on the characteristics of that implementation, providing binary compatibility between implementations.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] It also enables the evolution of the microarchitectures of the implementations of that ISA, so that a newer, higher-performance implementation of an ISA can run software that runs on previous generations of implementations.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] If an operating system maintains a standard and compatible application binary interface (ABI) for a particular ISA, machine code will run on future implementations of that ISA and operating system.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] However, if an ISA supports running multiple operating systems, it does not guarantee that machine code for one operating system will run on another operating system, unless the first operating system supports running machine code built for the other operating system.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] An ISA can be extended by adding instructions or other capabilities, or adding support for larger addresses and data values; an implementation of the extended ISA will still be able to execute machine code for versions of the ISA without those extensions.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Machine code using those extensions will only run on implementations that support those extensions.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] The binary compatibility that they provide makes ISAs one of the most fundamental abstractions in computing.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] An instruction set architecture is distinguished from a microarchitecture, which is the set of processor design techniques used, in a particular processor, to implement the instruction set.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Processors with different microarchitectures can share a common instruction set.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] For example, the Intel Pentium and the AMD Athlon implement nearly identical versions of the x86 instruction set, but they have radically different internal designs.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] The concept of an *architecture*, distinct from the design of a specific machine, was developed by Fred Brooks at IBM during the design phase of System/360.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Some virtual machines that support bytecode as their ISA such as Smalltalk, the Java virtual machine, and Microsoft's Common Language Runtime, implement this by translating the bytecode for commonly used code paths into native machine code.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] In addition, these virtual machines execute less frequently used code paths by interpretation (see: Just-in-time compilation).
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Transmeta implemented the x86 instruction set atop very long instruction word (VLIW) processors in this fashion.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] An ISA may be classified in a number of different ways.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] A common classification is by architectural *complexity*.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] A complex instruction set computer (CISC) has many specialized instructions, some of which may only be rarely used in practical programs.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Other types include VLIW architectures, and the closely related *long instruction word* (LIW) and *explicitly parallel instruction computing* (EPIC) architectures.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] These architectures seek to exploit instruction-level parallelism with less hardware than RISC and CISC by making the compiler responsible for instruction issue and scheduling.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Architectures with even less complexity have been studied, such as the minimal instruction set computer (MISC) and one-instruction set computer (OISC).
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] These are theoretically important types, but have not been commercialized.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Machine language is built up from discrete *statements* or *instructions*.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] More complex operations are built up by combining these simple instructions, which are executed sequentially, or as otherwise directed by control flow instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Processors may include elaborate instructions in their instruction set.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] A single elaborate instruction does something that may require many instructions or a subroutine on other computers.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Such instructions are typified by instructions that take multiple steps, control multiple functional units, or otherwise appear on a larger scale than the bulk of simple instructions implemented by the given processor.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Elaborate instructions are more common in CISC instruction sets than in RISC instruction sets, but RISC instruction sets may include them as well.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] RISC instruction sets generally do not include ALU operations with memory operands, or instructions to move large blocks of memory, but most RISC instruction sets include SIMD or vector instructions that perform the same arithmetic operation on multiple pieces of data at the same time.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] SIMD instructions have the ability of manipulating large vectors and matrices in minimal time.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] SIMD instructions allow easy parallelization of algorithms commonly involved in sound, image, and video processing.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Various SIMD implementations have been brought to market under trade names such as MMX, 3DNow!, and AltiVec.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] On traditional architectures, an instruction includes an opcode that specifies the operation to perform, such as *add contents of memory to register*—and zero or more operand specifiers, which may specify registers, memory locations, or literal data.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] The operand specifiers may have addressing modes determining their meaning or may be in fixed fields.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] In very long instruction word (VLIW) architectures, which include many microcode architectures, multiple simultaneous opcodes and operands are specified in a single instruction.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Some exotic instruction sets do not have an opcode field, such as transport triggered architectures (TTA), only operand(s).
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Most stack machines have "0-operand" instruction sets in which arithmetic and logical operations lack any operand specifier fields; only instructions that push operands onto the evaluation stack or that pop operands from the stack into variables have operand specifiers.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] The instruction set carries out most ALU actions with postfix (reverse Polish notation) operations that work only on the expression stack, not on data registers or arbitrary main memory cells.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] This can be very convenient for compiling high-level languages, because most arithmetic expressions can be easily translated into postfix notation.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Conditional instructions often have a predicate field—a few bits that encode the specific condition to cause an operation to be performed rather than not performed.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] For example, a conditional branch instruction will transfer control if the condition is true, so that execution proceeds to a different part of the program, and not transfer control if the condition is false, so that execution continues sequentially.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Some instruction sets also have conditional moves, so that the move will be executed, and the data stored in the target location, if the condition is true, and not executed, and the target location not modified, if the condition is false.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Similarly, IBM z/Architecture has a conditional store instruction.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] A few instruction sets include a predicate field in every instruction.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Having predicates on instructions is called predication, and can *include* conditional-branches, such as `bf` on the SuperH.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Many architectures have conditional branch instructions designed for controlling loops.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Typically, they update and test a register.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Instruction sets may be categorized by the maximum number of operands *explicitly* specified in instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Due to the large number of bits needed to encode the three registers of a 3-operand instruction, RISC architectures that have 16-bit instructions are invariably 2-operand designs, such as the Atmel AVR, TI MSP430, and some versions of ARM Thumb.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] RISC architectures that have 32-bit instructions are usually 3-operand designs, such as the ARM, AVR32, MIPS, Power ISA, and SPARC architectures.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] However even 3-operand RISC architectures will, at considerable cost, have Fused multiply-and-add 4-operand instructions out of necessity, due to the increased accuracy provided.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Modern examples include Power ISA and RISC-V.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Each instruction specifies some number of operands (registers, memory locations, or immediate values) *explicitly*.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Some instructions give one or both operands implicitly, such as by being stored on top of the stack or in an implicit register.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] If some of the operands are given implicitly, fewer operands need be specified in the instruction.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] When a "destination operand" explicitly specifies the destination, an additional operand must be supplied.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Consequently, the number of operands encoded in an instruction may differ from the mathematically necessary number of arguments for a logical or arithmetic operation (the arity).
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Operands are either encoded in the "opcode" representation of the instruction, or else are given as values or addresses following the opcode.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] While embedded instruction sets such as Thumb suffer from extremely high register pressure because they have small register sets, general-purpose RISC ISAs like MIPS and Alpha enjoy low register pressure.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] CISC ISAs like x86-64 offer low register pressure despite having smaller register sets.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] This is due to the many addressing modes and optimizations (such as sub-register addressing, memory operands in ALU instructions, absolute addressing, PC-relative addressing, and register-to-register spills) that CISC ISAs offer.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] The size or length of an instruction varies widely, from as little as four bits in some microcontrollers to many hundreds of bits in some VLIW systems.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Processors used in personal computers, mainframes, and supercomputers have minimum instruction sizes between 8 and 64 bits.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] The longest possible instruction on x86 is 15 bytes (120 bits).
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Within an instruction set, different instructions may have different lengths.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] In some architectures, notably most reduced instruction set computers (RISC), instructions are a fixed length, typically corresponding with that architecture's word size.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] In other architectures, instructions have variable length, typically integral multiples of a byte or a halfword.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Some, such as the ARM with *Thumb-extension* have *mixed* variable encoding, that is two fixed, usually 32-bit and 16-bit encodings, where instructions cannot be mixed freely but must be switched between on a branch (or exception boundary in ARMv8).
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Fixed-length instructions are less complicated to handle than variable-length instructions for several reasons (not having to check whether an instruction straddles a cache line or virtual memory page boundary, for instance), and are therefore somewhat easier to optimize for speed.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] In early 1960s computers, main memory was expensive and very limited, even on mainframes.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Minimizing the size of a program to make sure it would fit in the limited memory was often central.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Thus the size of the instructions needed to perform a particular task, the *code density*, was an important characteristic of any instruction set.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] It remained important on the initially-tiny memories of minicomputers and then microprocessors.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Density remains important today, for smartphone applications, applications downloaded into browsers over slow Internet connections, and in ROMs for embedded applications.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] A more general advantage of increased density is improved effectiveness of caches and instruction prefetch.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Computers with high code density often have complex instructions for procedure entry, parameterized returns, loops, etc.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] (therefore retroactively named *Complex Instruction Set Computers*, CISC).
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] However, more typical, or frequent, "CISC" instructions merely combine a basic ALU operation, such as "add", with the access of one or more operands in memory (using addressing modes such as direct, indirect, indexed, etc.).
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Certain architectures may allow two or three operands (including the result) directly in memory or may be able to perform functions such as automatic pointer increment, etc.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Software-implemented instruction sets may have even more complex and powerful instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Certain embedded RISC ISAs like Thumb and AVR32 typically exhibit very high density owing to a technique called code compression.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] This technique packs two 16-bit instructions into one 32-bit word, which is then unpacked at the decode stage and executed as two instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Minimal instruction set computers (MISC) are commonly a form of stack machine, where there are few separate instructions (8–32), so that multiple instructions can be fit into a single machine word.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] These types of cores often take little silicon to implement, so they can be easily realized in an FPGA (field-programmable gate array) or in a multi-core form.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] The code density of MISC is similar to the code density of RISC; the increased instruction density is offset by requiring more of the primitive instructions to do a task.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] There has been research into executable compression as a mechanism for improving code density.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] The mathematics of Kolmogorov complexity describes the challenges and limits of this.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] In practice, code density is also dependent on the compiler.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Most optimizing compilers have options that control whether to optimize code generation for execution speed or for code density.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] For instance GCC has the option `-Os` to optimize for small machine code size, and `-O3` to optimize for execution speed at the cost of larger machine code.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] The instructions constituting a program are rarely specified using their internal, numeric form (machine code); they may be specified by programmers using an assembly language or, more commonly, may be generated from high-level programming languages by compilers.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] The design of instruction sets is a complex issue.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] There were two stages in history for the microprocessor.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] The first was the CISC (complex instruction set computer), which had many different instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] In the 1970s, however, places like IBM did research and found that many instructions in the set could be eliminated.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] The result was the RISC (reduced instruction set computer), an architecture that uses a smaller set of instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] A simpler instruction set may offer the potential for higher speeds, reduced processor size, and reduced power consumption.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] However, a more complex set may optimize common operations, improve memory and cache efficiency, or simplify programming.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Some instruction set designers reserve one or more opcodes for some kind of system call or software interrupt.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] For example, MOS Technology 6502 uses 00H, Zilog Z80 uses the eight codes C7,CF,D7,DF,E7,EF,F7,FFH while Motorola 68000 use codes in the range 4E40H-4E4FH.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Fast virtual machines are much easier to implement if an instruction set meets the Popek and Goldberg virtualization requirements.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] The NOP slide used in immunity-aware programming is much easier to implement if the "unprogrammed" state of the memory is interpreted as a NOP.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] On systems with multiple processors, non-blocking synchronization algorithms are much easier to implement if the instruction set includes support for something such as "fetch-and-add", "load-link/store-conditional" (LL/SC), or "atomic compare-and-swap".
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] A given instruction set can be implemented in a variety of ways.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] All ways of implementing a particular instruction set provide the same programming model, and all implementations of that instruction set are able to run the same executables.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] The various ways of implementing an instruction set give different tradeoffs between cost, performance, power consumption, size, etc.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] When designing the microarchitecture of a processor, engineers use blocks of "hard-wired" electronic circuitry (often designed separately) such as adders, multiplexers, counters, registers, ALUs, etc.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Some kind of register transfer language is then often used to describe the decoding and sequencing of each instruction of an ISA using this physical microarchitecture.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Other designs employ microcode routines or tables (or both) to do this, using ROMs or writable RAMs (writable control store), PLAs, or both.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Some microcoded CPU designs with a writable control store use it to allow the instruction set to be changed (for example, the Rekursiv processor and the Imsys Cjip).
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] CPUs designed for reconfigurable computing may use field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs).
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] An ISA can also be emulated in software by an interpreter.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Naturally, due to the interpretation overhead, this is slower than directly running programs on the emulated hardware, unless the hardware running the emulator is an order of magnitude faster.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Today, it is common practice for vendors of new ISAs or microarchitectures to make software emulators available to software developers before the hardware implementation is ready.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] Often the details of the implementation have a strong influence on the particular instructions selected for the instruction set.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] For example, many implementations of the instruction pipeline only allow a single memory load or memory store per instruction, leading to a load–store architecture (RISC).
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] For another example, some early ways of implementing the instruction pipeline led to a delay slot.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] The demands of high-speed digital signal processing have pushed in the opposite direction—forcing instructions to be implemented in a particular way.
[src:mips-assembly/instruction-set-architecture] For example, to perform digital filters fast enough, the MAC instruction in a typical digital signal processor (DSP) must use a kind of Harvard architecture that can fetch an instruction and two data words simultaneously, and it requires a single-cycle multiply–accumulate multiplier.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] There are multiple versions of MIPS, including MIPS I, II, III, IV, and V, as well as five releases of MIPS32/64 (for 32- and 64-bit implementations, respectively).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The early MIPS architectures were 32-bit; 64-bit versions were developed later.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] As of April 2017, the current version of MIPS is MIPS32/64 Release 6.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS32/64 primarily differs from MIPS I–V by defining the privileged kernel mode System Control Coprocessor in addition to the user mode architecture.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Computer architecture courses in universities and technical schools often study the MIPS architecture.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The architecture greatly influenced later RISC architectures such as Alpha.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] In March 2021, MIPS announced that the development of the MIPS architecture had ended as the company is making the transition to RISC-V.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The first version of the MIPS architecture was designed by MIPS Computer Systems for its R2000 microprocessor, the first MIPS implementation.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Both MIPS and the R2000 were introduced together in 1985.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] When MIPS II was introduced, *MIPS* was renamed *MIPS I* to distinguish it from the new version.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS Computer Systems' R6000 microprocessor (1989) was the first MIPS II implementation.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Designed for servers, the R6000 was fabricated and sold by Bipolar Integrated Technology, but was a commercial failure.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] During the mid-1990s, many new 32-bit MIPS processors for embedded systems were MIPS II implementations because the introduction of the 64-bit MIPS III architecture in 1991 left MIPS II as the newest 32-bit MIPS architecture until MIPS32 was introduced in 1999.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS Computer Systems' R4000 microprocessor (1991) was the first MIPS III implementation.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] It was designed for use in personal, workstation, and server computers.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS Computer Systems aggressively promoted the MIPS architecture and R4000, establishing the Advanced Computing Environment (ACE) consortium to advance its Advanced RISC Computing (ARC) standard, which aimed to establish MIPS as the dominant personal computing platform.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] ARC found little success in personal computers, but the R4000 (and the R4400 derivative) were widely used in workstation and server computers, especially by its largest user, Silicon Graphics.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Other uses of the R4000 included high-end embedded systems and supercomputers.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS III was eventually implemented by a number of embedded microprocessors.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Quantum Effect Design's R4600 (1993) and its derivatives were widely used in high-end embedded systems and low-end workstations and servers.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS Technologies' R4200 (1994), was designed for embedded systems, laptop, and personal computers.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] A derivative, the R4300i, fabricated by NEC Electronics, was used in the Nintendo 64 game console.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The Nintendo 64, along with the PlayStation, were among the highest volume users of MIPS architecture processors in the mid-1990s.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The first MIPS IV implementation was the MIPS Technologies R8000 microprocessor chipset (1994).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The design of the R8000 began at Silicon Graphics, Inc. and it was only used in high-end workstations and servers for scientific and technical applications where high performance on large floating-point workloads was important.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Later implementations were the MIPS Technologies R10000 (1996) and the Quantum Effect Devices R5000 (1996) and RM7000 (1998).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The R10000, fabricated and sold by NEC Electronics and Toshiba, and its derivatives were used by NEC, Pyramid Technology, Silicon Graphics, and Tandem Computers (among others) in workstations, servers, and supercomputers.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The R5000 and R7000 found use in high-end embedded systems, personal computers, and low-end workstations and servers.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] A derivative of the R5000 from Toshiba, the R5900, was used in Sony Computer Entertainment's Emotion Engine, which powered its PlayStation 2 game console.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Announced on October 21, 1996, at the Microprocessor Forum 1996 alongside the MIPS Digital Media Extensions (MDMX) extension, MIPS V was designed to improve the performance of 3D graphics transformations.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] In the mid-1990s, a major use of non-embedded MIPS microprocessors were graphics workstations from Silicon Graphics.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS V was completed by the integer-only MDMX extension to provide a complete system for improving the performance of 3D graphics applications.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS V implementations were never introduced.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] On May 12, 1997, Silicon Graphics announced the H1 ("Beast") and H2 ("Capitan") microprocessors.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The former was to have been the first MIPS V implementation, and was due to be introduced in the first half of 1999.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The H1 and H2 projects were later combined and eventually canceled in 1998.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] While there have not been any MIPS V implementations, MIPS64 Release 1 (1999) was based on MIPS V and retains all of its features as an optional Coprocessor 1 (FPU) feature called Paired-Single.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] When MIPS Technologies was spun-out of Silicon Graphics in 1998, it refocused on the embedded market.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Through MIPS V, each successive version was a strict superset of the previous version, but this property was found to be a problem, and the architecture definition was changed to define a 32-bit and a 64-bit architecture: MIPS32 and MIPS64.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS32 is based on MIPS II with some additional features from MIPS III, MIPS IV, and MIPS V; MIPS64 is based on MIPS V.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] NEC, Toshiba and SiByte (later acquired by Broadcom) each obtained licenses for MIPS64 as soon as it was announced.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Philips, LSI Logic, IDT, Raza Microelectronics, Inc., Cavium, Loongson Technology and Ingenic Semiconductor have since joined them.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS32/MIPS64 Release 5 was announced on December 6, 2012.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] According to the Product Marketing Director at MIPS, Release 4 was skipped because the number four is perceived as unlucky in many Asian cultures.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] In December 2018, Wave Computing, the new owner of the MIPS architecture, announced that MIPS ISA would be open-sourced in a program dubbed the MIPS Open initiative.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The program was intended to open up access to the most recent versions of both the 32-bit and 64-bit designs making them available without any licensing or royalty fees as well as granting participants licenses to existing MIPS patents.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] In March 2019, MIPS Revision 6 was made available under a royalty-free license, but later that year the program was shut down again.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] In March 2021, Wave Computing announced that the development of the MIPS architecture has ceased.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The company has joined the RISC-V foundation and future processor designs will be based on the RISC-V architecture.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] In spite of this, some licensees such as Loongson are continuing with new extensions of MIPS-compatible ISAs on their own.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] In January 2024, Loongson won a case over rights to use MIPS architecture.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS is a modular architecture supporting up to four coprocessors (COP0/1/2/3).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] For example, in the PlayStation video game console, COP2 is the Geometry Transformation Engine (GTE), which accelerates the processing of geometry in 3D computer graphics.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS is a load/store architecture (also known as a *register-register architecture*); except for the load/store instructions used to access memory, all instructions operate on the registers.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS I has thirty-two 32-bit general-purpose registers (GPR).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Register $0 is hardwired to zero and writes to it are discarded.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] For integer multiplication and division instructions, which run asynchronously from other instructions, a pair of 32-bit registers, *HI* and *LO*, are provided.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] There is a small set of instructions for copying data between the general-purpose registers and the HI/LO registers.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The two low-order bits always contain zero since MIPS I instructions are 32 bits long and are aligned to their natural word boundaries.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Instructions are divided into three types: R (register), I (immediate), and J (jump).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Every instruction starts with a 6-bit opcode.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] In addition to the opcode, R-type instructions specify three registers, a shift amount field, and a function field; I-type instructions specify two registers and a 16-bit immediate value; J-type instructions follow the opcode with a 26-bit jump target.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS I has instructions that load and store 8-bit bytes, 16-bit halfwords, and 32-bit words.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Only one addressing mode is supported: base + displacement.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Since MIPS I is a 32-bit architecture, loading quantities fewer than 32 bits requires the datum to be either sign-extended or zero-extended to 32 bits.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The load instructions suffixed by "unsigned" perform zero extension; otherwise sign extension is performed.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Load instructions source the base from the contents of a GPR (rs) and write the result to another GPR (rt).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Store instructions source the base from the contents of a GPR (rs) and the store data from another GPR (rt).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] All load and store instructions compute the memory address by summing the base with the sign-extended 16-bit immediate.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS I requires all memory accesses to be aligned to their natural word boundaries, otherwise an exception is signaled.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] To support efficient unaligned memory accesses, there are load/store word instructions suffixed by "left" or "right".
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] All load instructions are followed by a load delay slot.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The instruction in the load delay slot cannot use the data loaded by the load instruction.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The load delay slot can be filled with an instruction that is not dependent on the load; a NOP is substituted if such an instruction cannot be found.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS I has instructions to perform addition and subtraction.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] These instructions source their operands from two GPRs (rs and rt), and write the result to a third GPR (rd).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Alternatively, addition can source one of the operands from a 16-bit immediate (which is sign-extended to 32 bits).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The instructions for addition and subtraction have two variants: by default, an exception is signaled if the result overflows; instructions with the "unsigned" suffix do not signal an exception.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The overflow check interprets the result as a 32-bit two's complement integer.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS I has instructions to perform bitwise logical AND, OR, XOR, and NOR.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] These instructions source their operands from two GPRs and write the result to a third GPR.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The AND, OR, and XOR instructions can alternatively source one of the operands from a 16-bit immediate (which is zero-extended to 32 bits).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The "Set on *relation*" instructions write one or zero to the destination register if the specified relation is true or false.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] These instructions source their operands from two GPRs or one GPR and a 16-bit immediate (which is sign-extended to 32 bits), and write the result to a third GPR.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] By default, the operands are interpreted as signed integers.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The variants of these instructions that are suffixed with "unsigned" interpret the operands as unsigned integers (even those that source an operand from the sign-extended 16-bit immediate).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The Load Upper Immediate instruction copies the 16-bit immediate into the high-order 16 bits of a GPR.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] It is used in conjunction with the Or Immediate instruction to load a 32-bit immediate into a register.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS I has instructions to perform left and right logical shifts and right arithmetic shifts.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The operand is obtained from a GPR (rt), and the result is written to another GPR (rd).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The shift distance is obtained from either a GPR (rs) or a 5-bit "shift amount" (the "sa" field).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS I has instructions for signed and unsigned integer multiplication and division.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] These instructions source their operands from two GPRs and write their results to a pair of 32-bit registers called HI and LO, since they may execute separately from (and concurrently with) the other CPU instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] For multiplication, the high- and low-order halves of the 64-bit product is written to HI and LO (respectively).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] For division, the quotient is written to LO and the remainder to HI.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] To access the results, a pair of instructions (Move from HI and Move from LO) is provided to copy the contents of HI or LO to a GPR.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] These instructions are interlocked: reads of HI and LO do not proceed past an unfinished arithmetic instruction that will write to HI and LO.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Another pair of instructions (Move to HI or Move to LO) copies the contents of a GPR to HI and LO.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] These instructions are used to restore HI and LO to their original state after exception handling.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Instructions that read HI or LO must be separated by two instructions that do not write to HI or LO.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] All MIPS I control flow instructions are followed by a branch delay slot.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Unless the branch delay slot is filled by an instruction performing useful work, a NOP is substituted.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS I branch instructions compare the contents of a GPR (rs) against zero or another GPR (rt) as signed integers and branch if the specified condition is true.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Control is transferred to the address computed by shifting the 16-bit offset left by two bits, sign-extending the 18-bit result, and adding the 32-bit sign-extended result to the sum of the program counter (instruction address) and 810.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Jumps have two versions: absolute and register-indirect.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Absolute jumps ("Jump" and "Jump and Link") compute the address to which control is transferred by shifting the 26-bit instr_index left by two bits and concatenating the 28-bit result with the four high-order bits of the address of the instruction in the branch delay slot.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Register-indirect jumps transfer control to the instruction at the address sourced from a GPR (rs).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The address sourced from the GPR must be word-aligned, else an exception is signaled after the instruction in the branch delay slot is executed.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Branch and jump instructions that link (except for "Jump and Link Register") save the return address to GPR 31.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The "Jump and Link Register" instruction permits the return address to be saved to any writable GPR.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS I has two instructions for software to signal an exception: System Call and Breakpoint.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] System Call is used by user mode software to make kernel calls; and Breakpoint is used to transfer control to a debugger via the kernel's exception handler.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Both instructions have a 20-bit Code field that can contain operating environment-specific information for the exception handler.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Two registers are paired for double precision numbers.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Odd numbered registers cannot be used for arithmetic or branching, just as part of a double precision register pair, resulting in 16 usable registers for most instructions (moves/copies and loads/stores were not affected).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Single precision is denoted by the .s suffix, while double precision is denoted by the .d suffix.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS II removed the load delay slot and added several sets of instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] For shared-memory multiprocessing, the *Synchronize Shared Memory*, *Load Linked Word*, and *Store Conditional Word* instructions were added.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] A set of Trap-on-Condition instructions were added.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] These instructions caused an exception if the evaluated condition is true.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] All existing branch instructions were given *branch-likely* versions that executed the instruction in the branch delay slot only if the branch is taken.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] These instructions improve performance in certain cases by allowing useful instructions to fill the branch delay slot.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Doubleword load and store instructions for COP1–3 were added.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Consistent with other memory access instructions, these loads and stores required the doubleword to be naturally aligned.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The instruction set for the floating point coprocessor also had several instructions added to it.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] An IEEE 754-compliant floating-point square root instruction was added.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] It supported both single- and double-precision operands.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] A set of instructions that converted single- and double-precision floating-point numbers to 32-bit words were added.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] These complemented the existing conversion instructions by allowing the IEEE rounding mode to be specified by the instruction instead of the Floating Point Control and Status Register.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS III is a backwards-compatible extension of MIPS II that added support for 64-bit memory addressing and integer operations.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The 64-bit data type is called a doubleword, and MIPS III extended the general-purpose registers, HI/LO registers, and program counter to 64 bits to support it.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] New instructions were added to load and store doublewords, to perform integer addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, and shift operations on them, and to move doubleword between the GPRs and HI/LO registers.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] For shared-memory multiprocessing, the *Load Linked Double Word*, and *Store Conditional Double Word* instructions were added.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Existing instructions originally defined to operate on 32-bit words were redefined, where necessary, to sign-extend the 32-bit results to permit words and doublewords to be treated identically by most instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Among those instructions redefined was *Load Word*.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] In MIPS III it sign-extends words to 64 bits.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] To complement *Load Word*, a version that zero-extends was added.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The R instruction format's inability to specify the full shift distance for 64-bit shifts (its 5-bit shift amount field is too narrow to specify the shift distance for doublewords) required MIPS III to provide three 64-bit versions of each MIPS I shift instruction.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The first version is a 64-bit version of the original shift instructions, used to specify constant shift distances of 0–31 bits.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The second version is similar to the first, but adds 3210 the shift amount field's value so that constant shift distances of 32–63 bits can be specified.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The third version obtains the shift distance from the six low-order bits of a GPR.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS III added a *supervisor* privilege level in between the existing kernel and user privilege levels.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] This feature only affected the implementation-defined System Control Processor (Coprocessor 0).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS III removed the Coprocessor 3 (COP3) support instructions, and reused its opcodes for the new doubleword instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The remaining coprocessors gained instructions to move doublewords between coprocessor registers and the GPRs.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The floating general registers (FGRs) were extended to 64 bits and the requirement for instructions to use even-numbered register only was removed.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] This is incompatible with earlier versions of the architecture; a bit in the floating-point control/status register is used to operate the MIPS III floating-point unit (FPU) in a MIPS I- and II-compatible mode.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The floating-point control registers were not extended for compatibility.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The only new floating-point instructions added were those to copy doublewords between the CPU and FPU convert single- and double-precision floating-point numbers into doubleword integers and vice versa.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS IV is the fourth version of the architecture.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] It is a superset of MIPS III and is compatible with all existing versions of MIPS.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS IV was designed to mainly improve floating-point (FP) performance.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] To improve access to operands, an indexed addressing mode (base + index, both sourced from GPRs) for FP loads and stores was added, as were prefetch instructions for performing memory prefetching and specifying cache hints (these supported both the base + offset and base + index addressing modes).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS IV added several features to improve instruction-level parallelism.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] To alleviate the bottleneck caused by a single condition bit, seven condition code bits were added to the floating-point control and status register, bringing the total to eight.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] FP comparison and branch instructions were redefined so they could specify which condition bit was written or read (respectively); and the delay slot in between an FP branch that read the condition bit written to by a prior FP comparison was removed.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Support for partial predication was added in the form of conditional move instructions for both GPRs and FPRs; and an implementation could choose between having precise or imprecise exceptions for IEEE 754 traps.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS IV added several new FP arithmetic instructions for both single- and double-precision FPNs: fused-multiply add or subtract, reciprocal, and reciprocal square-root.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The FP fused-multiply add or subtract instructions perform either one or two roundings (it is implementation-defined), to exceed or meet IEEE 754 accuracy requirements (respectively).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The FP reciprocal and reciprocal square-root instructions do not comply with IEEE 754 accuracy requirements, and produce results that differ from the required accuracy by one or two units of last place (it is implementation defined).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] These instructions serve applications where instruction latency is more important than accuracy.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS V added a new data type, the Paired Single (PS), which consisted of two single-precision (32-bit) floating-point numbers stored in the existing 64-bit floating-point registers.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Variants of existing floating-point instructions for arithmetic, compare and conditional move were added to operate on this data type in a SIMD fashion.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] New instructions were added for loading, rearranging and converting PS data.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] It was the first instruction set to exploit floating-point SIMD with existing resources.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The first release of MIPS32, based on MIPS II, added conditional moves, prefetch instructions, and other features from the R4000 and R5000 families of 64-bit processors.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The first release of MIPS64 adds a MIPS32 mode to run 32-bit code.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The MUL and MADD (multiply-add) instructions, previously available in some implementations, were added to the MIPS32 and MIPS64 specifications, as were cache control instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] For the purpose of cache control, both `SYNC` and `SYNCI` instructions were prepared.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Reorganized the instruction encoding, freeing space for future expansions.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The microMIPS32/64 architectures are supersets of the MIPS32 and MIPS64 architectures (respectively) designed to replace the MIPS16e application-specific extension (ASE).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] A disadvantage of MIPS16e is that it requires a mode switch before any of its 16-bit instructions can be processed. microMIPS adds versions of the most-frequently used 32-bit instructions that are encoded as 16-bit instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] This allows programs to intermix 16- and 32-bit instructions without having to switch modes. microMIPS was introduced alongside of MIPS32/64 Release 3, and each subsequent release of MIPS32/64 has a corresponding microMIPS32/64 version.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] A processor may implement microMIPS32/64 or both microMIPS32/64 and its corresponding MIPS32/64 subset.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Starting with MIPS32/64 Release 6, support for MIPS16e ended, and microMIPS is the only form of code compression in MIPS.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The base MIPS32 and MIPS64 architectures can be supplemented with a number of optional architectural extensions, which are collectively referred to as *application-specific extensions* (ASEs).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] These ASEs provide features that improve the efficiency and performance of certain workloads, such as digital signal processing.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Enhancements for microcontroller applications.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The MCU ASE (application-specific extension) has been developed to extend the interrupt controller support, reduce the interrupt latency and enhance the I/O peripheral control function typically required in microcontroller system designs.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS16 is an Application-Specific Extension for MIPS I through to V designed by LSI Logic and MIPS Technologies, announced on October 21, 1996, alongside its first implementation, the LSI Logic TinyRISC processor.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS16 was subsequently licensed by NEC Electronics, Philips Semiconductors, and Toshiba (among others); and implemented as an extension to the MIPS I, II, an III architectures.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS16 decreases the size of application by up to 40% by using 16-bit instructions instead of 32-bit instructions and also improves power efficiency, the instruction cache hit rate, and is equivalent in performance to its base architecture.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] It is supported by hardware and software development tools from MIPS Technologies and other providers.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS16e is an improved version of MIPS16 first supported by MIPS32 and MIPS64 Release 1.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS16e2 is an improved version of MIPS16 that is supported by MIPS32 and MIPS64 (up to Release 5).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The DSP ASE is an optional extension to the MIPS32/MIPS64 Release 2 and newer instruction sets which can be used to accelerate a large range of "media" computations—particularly audio and video.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The DSP module comprises a set of instructions and state in the integer pipeline and requires minimal additional logic to implement in MIPS processor cores.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Revision 2 of the ASE was introduced in the second half of 2006.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] This revision adds extra instructions to the original ASE, but is otherwise backwards-compatible with it.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Unlike the bulk of the MIPS architecture, it's a fairly irregular set of operations, many chosen for a particular relevance to some key algorithm.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Instruction set extensions designed to accelerate multimedia.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS Revision 6 added native virtualization supported by hardware.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Each multi-threaded MIPS core can support up to two VPEs (Virtual Processing Elements) which share a single pipeline as well as other hardware resources.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] However, since each VPE includes a complete copy of the processor state as seen by the software system, each VPE appears as a complete standalone processor to an SMP Linux operating system.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] For more fine-grained thread processing applications, each VPE is capable of supporting up to nine TCs allocated across two VPEs.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The TCs share a common execution unit but each has its own program counter and core register files so that each can handle a thread from the software.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The MIPS MT architecture also allows the allocation of processor cycles to threads, and sets the relative thread priorities with an optional Quality of Service (QoS) manager block.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] This enables two prioritization mechanisms that determine the flow of information across the bus.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The first mechanism allows the user to prioritize one thread over another.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The second mechanism is used to allocate a specified ratio of the cycles to specific threads over time.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The combined use of both mechanisms allows effective allocation of bandwidth to the set of threads, and better control of latencies.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] In real-time systems, system-level determinism is very critical, and the QoS block facilitates improvement of the predictability of a system.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Hardware designers of advanced systems may replace the standard QoS block provided by MIPS Technologies with one that is specifically tuned for their application.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] SmartMIPS is an Application-Specific Extension (ASE) designed by Gemplus International and MIPS Technologies to improve performance and reduce memory consumption for smart card software.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] It is supported by MIPS32 only, since smart cards do not require the capabilities of MIPS64 processors.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Multimedia application accelerations that were common in the 1990s on RISC and CISC systems.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS has had several calling conventions, especially on the 32-bit platform.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The O32 ABI is the most commonly used ABI, owing to its status as the original System V ABI for MIPS.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] It is strictly stack-based, with only four registers ($a0-$a3) available to pass arguments.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Space on the stack is reserved in case the callee needs to save its arguments, but the registers are not stored there by the caller.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The return value is stored in register $v0; a second return value may be stored in $v1.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The ABI took shape in 1990 and was last updated in 1994.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] This perceived slowness, along with an antiquated floating-point model with only 16 registers, has encouraged the proliferation of many other calling conventions.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] It is only defined for 32-bit MIPS, but GCC has created a 64-bit variation called O64.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] For 64-bit, the N64 ABI by Silicon Graphics is most commonly used.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The most important improvement is that eight registers are now available for argument passing; it also increases the number of floating-point registers to 32.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] There is also an ILP32 version called N32, which uses 32-bit pointers for smaller code, analogous to the x32 ABI.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Both run under the 64-bit mode of the CPU.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The N32 and N64 ABIs pass the first eight arguments to a function in the registers $a0-$a7; subsequent arguments are passed on the stack.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The return value (or a pointer to it) is stored in $v0; a second return value may be stored in $v1.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] In both the N32 and N64 ABIs, all registers are considered to be 64-bits wide.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] A few attempts have been made to replace O32 with a 32-bit ABI that resembles N32 more than O32.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] A 1995 conference came up with MIPS EABI, for which the 32-bit version was quite similar.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] EABI inspired MIPS Technologies to propose a more radical "NUBI" ABI additionally reuse argument registers for the return value.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS EABI is supported by GCC but not LLVM, and neither supports NUBI.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] For all of O32 and N32/N64, the return address is stored in $ra ($31).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] This is automatically set with the use of the JAL (jump and link) or JALR (jump and link register) instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The function prologue of a (non-leaf) MIPS subroutine pushes the return address (in $ra) to the stack.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] On both O32 and N32/N64, the stack grows downwards, but the N32/N64 ABIs require 64-bit alignment for all stack entries.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The frame pointer ($30) is optional and in practice rarely used except when the stack allocation in a function is determined at runtime, for example, by calling `alloca()`.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] For N32 and N64, the return address is typically stored 8 bytes before the stack pointer, although this may be optional.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] For the N32 and N64 ABIs, a function must preserve the $s0-$s7 registers, the global pointer ($gp or $28), the stack pointer ($sp or $29) and the frame pointer ($fp or $30).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The O32 ABI is the same except the calling function is required to save the $gp register instead of the called function.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] For multi-threaded code, the thread local storage pointer is typically stored in special hardware register $29 and is accessed by using the mfhw (move from hardware) instruction.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] At least one vendor is known to store this information in the $k0 register which is normally reserved for kernel use, but this is not standard.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The $k0 and $k1 registers ($26, $27) are reserved for kernel use and should not be used by applications since these registers can be changed at any time by the kernel due to interrupts, context switches or other events.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Registers that are preserved across a call are registers that (by convention) will not be changed by a system call or procedure (function) call.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] For example, $s-registers must be saved to the stack by a procedure that needs to use them, and $sp and $fp are always incremented by constants, and decremented back after the procedure is done with them (and the memory they point to).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] By contrast, $ra is changed automatically by any normal function call (ones that use jal), and $t-registers must be saved by the program before any procedure call (if the program needs the values inside them after the call).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The userspace calling convention of position-independent code on Linux additionally requires that when a function is called the $t9 register must contain the address of that function.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] This convention dates back to the System V ABI supplement for MIPS.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS processors are used in embedded systems such as residential gateways and routers.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Originally, MIPS was designed for general-purpose computing.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] During the 1980s and 1990s, MIPS processors for personal, workstation, and server computers were used by many companies such as Digital Equipment Corporation, MIPS Computer Systems, NEC, Pyramid Technology, SiCortex, Siemens Nixdorf, Silicon Graphics, and Tandem Computers.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Historically, video game consoles such as the Nintendo 64, Sony PlayStation, PlayStation 2, and PlayStation Portable used MIPS processors.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MIPS processors also used to be popular in supercomputers during the 1990s, but all such systems have dropped off the TOP500 list.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] These uses were complemented by embedded applications at first, but during the 1990s, MIPS became a major presence in the embedded processor market, and by the 2000s, most MIPS processors were for these applications.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] In the mid- to late-1990s, it was estimated that one in three RISC microprocessors produced was a MIPS processor.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] By the late 2010s, MIPS machines were still commonly used in embedded markets, including automotive, wireless router, LTE modems (mainly via MediaTek), and microcontrollers (for example the Microchip Technology PIC32M).
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] They have mostly faded out of the personal, server, and application space.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Open Virtual Platforms (OVP) includes the freely available for non-commercial use simulator OVPsim, a library of models of processors, peripherals and platforms, and APIs which enable users to develop their own models.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The models in the library are open source, written in C, and include the MIPS 4K, 24K, 34K, 74K, 1004K, 1074K, M14K, microAptiv, interAptiv, proAptiv 32-bit cores and the MIPS 64-bit 5K range of cores.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] These models are created and maintained by Imperas and in partnership with MIPS Technologies have been tested and assigned the MIPS-Verified mark.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Sample MIPS-based platforms include both bare metal environments and platforms for booting unmodified Linux binary images.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] These platforms–emulators are available as source or binaries and are fast, free for non-commercial usage, and are easy to use.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] OVPsim is developed and maintained by Imperas and is very fast (hundreds of million of instructions per second), and built to handle multicore homogeneous and heterogeneous architectures and systems.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] SPIM is a freely available MIPS32 simulator for use in education.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Its newest version is called QtSpim and uses the Qt UI framework.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] EduMIPS64 is a GPL graphical cross-platform MIPS64 CPU simulator written in Java/Swing, it started as a port of WinMIPS64, another MIPS64 simulator, and supports a wide subset of the MIPS64 ISA and allows the user to graphically see what happens in the pipeline when an assembly program is run.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] MARS is another GUI-based MIPS emulator designed for use in education, specifically for use with Hennessy's *Computer Organization and Design*.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Saturn is a GUI-based MIPS IDE with an assembler called Titan.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] It started as a project by a student at the University of Toronto as a replacement for MARS, which is no longer maintained.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Saturn is now used in courses at the University of Toronto, and is maintained by students and faculty.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] WebMIPS is a browser-based MIPS simulator with visual representation of a generic, pipelined processor.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] This simulator is quite useful for register tracking during step by step execution.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] QtMips provides a simple 5-stage pipeline visualization as well as cache principle visualization for basic computer architectures courses.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] It is available both as a web application and as a downloadable program for Windows, Linux, and macOS.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] More advanced free emulators are available from the GXemul (formerly known as the mips64emul project) and QEMU projects.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] They emulate the various MIPS III and IV microprocessors in addition to entire computer systems which use them.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] The CREATOR simulator is portable and allows the user to learn various assembly languages of different processors.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] Creator has examples with an implementation of MIPS32 and RISC-V instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/mips-architecture] WepSIM is a browser-based simulator where a subset of MIPS instructions are micro-programmed.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] A **processor register** is a quickly accessible storage location available to a computer's processor.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] Registers usually consist of a small amount of fast storage, although some registers have specific hardware functions, and may be read-only or write-only.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] In computer architecture, registers are typically addressed by mechanisms other than main memory, but may in some cases be assigned a memory address e.g. the DEC PDP-6/PDP-10 and the ICT 1900.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] Almost all computers, whether load/store architecture or not, load items of data from a larger memory into registers where they are used for arithmetic operations, bitwise operations, and other operations, and are manipulated or tested by machine instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] Manipulated items are then often stored back to main memory, either by the same instruction or by a subsequent one.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] Modern processors use either static or dynamic random-access memory (RAM) as main memory, with the latter usually accessed via one or more cache levels.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] Processor registers are normally at the top of the memory hierarchy, and provide the fastest way to access data.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] The term normally refers only to the group of registers that are directly encoded as part of an instruction, as defined by the instruction set.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] However, modern high-performance CPUs often have duplicates of these "architectural registers" in order to improve performance via register renaming, allowing parallel and speculative execution.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] Modern x86 design acquired these techniques around 1995 with the releases of Pentium Pro, Cyrix 6x86, Nx586, and AMD K5.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] When a computer program accesses the same data repeatedly, this is called locality of reference.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] Holding frequently used values in registers can be critical to a program's performance.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] Register allocation is performed either by a compiler in the code generation phase, or manually by an assembly language programmer.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] Registers are normally measured by the number of bits they can hold, for example, an *8-bit register*, *32-bit register*, *64-bit register*, *128-bit register*, or more.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] In some instruction sets, the registers can operate in various modes, breaking down their storage memory into smaller parts (32-bit into four 8-bit ones, for instance) to which multiple data (vector, or one-dimensional array of data) can be loaded and operated upon at the same time.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] Typically it is implemented by adding extra registers that map their memory into a larger register.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] Processors that have the ability to execute single instructions on multiple data are called SIMD processors.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] In some architectures (such as SPARC and MIPS), the first or last register in the integer register file is a *pseudo-register* in that it is hardwired to always return zero when read (mostly to simplify indexing modes), and it cannot be overwritten.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] In Alpha, this is also done for the floating-point register file.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] As a result of this, register files are commonly quoted as having one register more than how many of them are actually usable; for example, 32 registers are quoted when only 31 of them fit within the above definition of a register.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] The following table shows the number of registers in several mainstream CPU architectures.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] Although all of the below-listed architectures are different, almost all are in a basic arrangement known as the von Neumann architecture, first proposed by the Hungarian-American mathematician John von Neumann.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] It is also noteworthy that the number of registers on GPUs is much higher than that on CPUs.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] The number of registers available on a processor and the operations that can be performed using those registers has a significant impact on the efficiency of code generated by optimizing compilers.
[src:mips-assembly/processor-register] The Strahler number of an expression tree gives the minimum number of registers required to evaluate that expression tree.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In electronics and computer science, a **reduced instruction set computer** (**RISC**, pronounced "risk") is a computer architecture designed to simplify the individual instructions given to the computer to accomplish tasks.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Compared to the instructions given to a complex instruction set computer (CISC), a RISC computer might require more machine code in order to accomplish a task because the individual instructions perform simpler operations.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The goal is to offset the need to process more instructions by increasing the speed of each instruction, in particular by implementing an instruction pipeline, which may be simpler to achieve given simpler instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The key operational concept of the RISC computer is that each instruction performs only one function (e.g., copy a value from memory to a register).
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The design of the CPU allows RISC computers few and simple addressing modes and predictable instruction times that simplify design of the system as a whole.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The conceptual developments of the RISC computer architecture began with the IBM 801 project in the late 1970s, but these were not immediately put into use.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Designers in California picked up the 801 concepts in two seminal projects, Stanford MIPS and Berkeley RISC.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] These were commercialized in the 1980s as the MIPS and SPARC systems.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] IBM eventually produced RISC designs based on further work on the 801 concept, the IBM POWER architecture, PowerPC, and Power ISA.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] RISC processors are used in supercomputers, such as the Fugaku.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The varieties of RISC processor design include the ARC processor, the DEC Alpha, the AMD Am29000, the ARM architecture, the Atmel AVR, Blackfin, Intel i860, Intel i960, LoongArch, Motorola 88000, the MIPS architecture, PA-RISC, Power ISA, RISC-V, SuperH, and SPARC.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] A number of systems, going back to the 1960s, have been credited as the first RISC architecture, partly based on their use of the load–store approach.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The term RISC was coined by David Patterson of the Berkeley RISC project, although somewhat similar concepts had appeared before.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The CDC 6600 designed by Seymour Cray in 1964 used a load–store architecture with only two addressing modes (register+register, and register+immediate constant) and 74 operation codes, with the basic clock cycle being 10 times faster than the memory access time.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Partly due to the optimized load–store architecture of the CDC 6600, Jack Dongarra says that it can be considered a forerunner of modern RISC systems, although a number of other technical barriers needed to be overcome for the development of a modern RISC system.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Flynn views the first RISC system as the IBM 801 design, begun in 1975 by John Cocke and completed in 1980.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The 801 developed out of an effort to build a 24-bit high-speed processor to use as the basis for a digital telephone switch.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] To reach their goal of switching 1 million calls per hour (300 per second) they calculated that the CPU required performance on the order of 12 million instructions per second (MIPS), compared to their fastest mainframe machine of the time, the 370/168, which performed at 3.5 MIPS.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The design was based on a study of IBM's extensive collection of statistics gathered from its customers.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This demonstrated that code in high-performance settings made extensive use of processor registers, and that they often ran out of them.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This suggested that additional registers would improve performance.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Additionally, they noticed that compilers generally ignored the vast majority of the available instructions, especially orthogonal addressing modes.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Instead, they selected the fastest version of any given instruction and then constructed small routines using it.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This suggested that the majority of instructions could be removed without affecting the resulting code.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] These two conclusions worked in concert; removing instructions would allow the instruction opcodes to be shorter, freeing up bits in the instruction word which could then be used to select among a larger set of registers.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The telephone switch program was canceled in 1975, but by then the team had demonstrated that the same design would offer significant performance gains running just about any code.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In simulations, they showed that a compiler tuned to use registers instead of operating directly on memory would run code about three times as fast as traditional designs.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Somewhat surprisingly, the same code would run about 50% faster even on existing machines due to the improved register use.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In practice, their experimental PL/8 compiler, a slightly cut-down version of PL/I, consistently produced code that ran much faster on their existing mainframes.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] A 32-bit version of the 801 was eventually produced in a single-chip form as the IBM ROMP in 1981, which stood for 'Research OPD [Office Products Division] Micro Processor'.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This CPU was designed for "mini" tasks, and found use in peripheral interfaces and channel controllers on later IBM computers.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] It was also used as the CPU in the IBM RT PC in 1986, which turned out to be a commercial failure.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Although the 801 did not see widespread use in its original form, it inspired many research projects, including ones at IBM that would eventually lead to the IBM POWER architecture.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] By the late 1970s, the 801 had become well-known in the industry.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This coincided with new fabrication techniques that were allowing more complex chips to come to market.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] These newer designs generally used their newfound complexity to expand the instruction set to make it more orthogonal.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Most, like the 68k, used microcode to do this, reading instructions and re-implementing them as a sequence of simpler internal instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In the 68k, a full 1⁄3 of the transistors were used for this microcoding.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In 1979, David Patterson was sent on a sabbatical from the University of California, Berkeley to help DEC's west-coast team improve the VAX microcode.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Patterson was struck by the complexity of the coding process and concluded it was untenable.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] He first wrote a paper on ways to improve microcoding, but later changed his mind and decided microcode itself was the problem.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] With funding from the DARPA VLSI Program, Patterson started the Berkeley RISC effort.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The program, practically unknown today, led to a huge number of advances in chip design, fabrication, and even computer graphics.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Considering a variety of programs from their BSD Unix variant, the Berkeley team found, as had IBM, that most programs made no use of the large variety of instructions in the 68k.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Patterson's early work pointed out an important problem with the traditional "more is better" approach; even those instructions that were critical to overall performance were being delayed by their trip through the microcode.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] If the microcode was removed, the programs would run faster.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] And since the microcode ultimately took a complex instruction and broke it into steps, there was no reason the compiler could not do this instead.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] These studies suggested that, even with no other changes, one could make a chip with 1⁄3 fewer transistors that would run faster.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] It was also discovered that, on microcoded implementations of certain architectures, complex operations tended to be *slower* than a sequence of simpler operations doing the same thing.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] One infamous example was the VAX's `INDEX` instruction.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The Berkeley work also turned up a number of additional points.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Among these was the fact that programs spent a significant amount of time performing subroutine calls and returns, and it seemed there was the potential to improve overall performance by speeding up these calls.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This led the Berkeley design to select a method known as register windows, which can significantly improve subroutine performance, although at the cost of some complexity.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] They also noticed that the majority of mathematical instructions were simple assignments; only 1⁄3 of them actually performed an operation like addition or subtraction.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] But when those operations did occur, they tended to be slow.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This led to far more emphasis on the underlying arithmetic data unit, as opposed to previous designs where the majority of the chip was dedicated to control and microcode.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The resulting Berkeley RISC was based on gaining performance through the use of pipelining and aggressive use of register windowing.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In a traditional CPU, one has a small number of registers, and a program can use any register at any time.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In a CPU with register windows, there are a huge number of registers, e.g., 128, but programs can only use a small number of them, e.g., eight, at any one time.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] A program that limits itself to eight registers per procedure can make very fast procedure calls: The call simply moves the window "down" by eight, to the set of eight registers used by that procedure, and the return moves the window back.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The Berkeley RISC project delivered the RISC-I processor in 1982.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Consisting of only 44,420 transistors (compared with averages of about 100,000 in newer CISC designs of the era), RISC-I had only 32 instructions, and yet completely outperformed any other single-chip design, with estimated performance being higher than the VAX.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] They followed this up with the 40,760-transistor, 39-instruction RISC-II in 1983, which ran over three times as fast as RISC-I.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] As the RISC project began to become known in Silicon Valley, a similar project began at Stanford University in 1981.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This MIPS project grew out of a graduate course by John L.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Hennessy, produced a functioning system in 1983, and could run simple programs by 1984.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The MIPS approach emphasized an aggressive clock cycle and the use of the pipeline, making sure it could be run as "full" as possible.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The MIPS system was followed by the MIPS-X, and in 1984 Hennessy and his colleagues formed MIPS Computer Systems to produce the design commercially.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The venture resulted in a new architecture that was also called MIPS and the R2000 microprocessor in 1985.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Competition between RISC and conventional CISC approaches was also the subject of theoretical analysis in the early 1980s, leading, for example, to the iron law of processor performance.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Since 2010, a new open standard instruction set architecture (ISA), Berkeley RISC-V, has been under development at the University of California, Berkeley, for research purposes and as a free alternative to proprietary ISAs.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] As of 2014, version 2 of the user space ISA is fixed.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The ISA is designed to be extensible from a barebones core sufficient for a small embedded processor to supercomputer and cloud computing use with standard and chip designer–defined extensions and coprocessors.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] It has been tested in silicon design with the ROCKET SoC, which is also available as an open-source processor generator in the CHISEL language.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In the early 1980s, significant uncertainties surrounded the RISC concept.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] One concern involved the use of memory; a single instruction from a traditional processor like the Motorola 68k may be written out as perhaps a half dozen of the simpler RISC instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In theory, this could slow the system down as it spends more time fetching instructions from memory.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] But by the mid-1980s, the concepts had matured enough to be seen as commercially viable.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In the minicomputer market, companies including Celerity Computing, Pyramid Technology, and Ridge Computers began offering systems designed according to RISC or RISC-like principles in the early 1980s.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Few of these designs began by using RISC microprocessors.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Commercial RISC designs began to emerge in the mid-1980s.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The IBM RT PC was introduced in January 1986, and the Acorn ARM1 was introduced as part of an evaluation system in July 1986, following on from initial fabrication in April 1985.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The MIPS R2000 was introduced in May 1986, followed shortly thereafter by Hewlett-Packard's PA-RISC in some of their computers.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In the meantime, the Berkeley effort had become so well known that it eventually became the name for the entire concept.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In 1987, Sun Microsystems began shipping systems with the SPARC processor, directly based on the Berkeley RISC-II system.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The US government Committee on Innovations in Computing and Communications credits the acceptance of the viability of the RISC concept to the success of the SPARC system.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] A benefit of RISC to the industry was much lower prices than the sole sourced Intel 80386; by 1989 many RISC CPUs were available, and competition lowered their price to $10 per MIPS in large quantities.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The performance of IBM's RISC CPU—only available in the RT PC—was less competitive than others, but the success of SPARC renewed interest within IBM, which released new RISC systems by 1990 and by 1995 RISC processors were the foundation of a $15 billion server industry.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Patterson was a consultant for Intel during the 1980s.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Despite dominating the microprocessor market with the CISC 80386 and its successors, the consensus that RISC was the future of the industry influenced that company's engineers, who worked to improve the performance of their processors to match RISC.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] IBM chose a similar approach of improving CISC as much as possible with IBM mainframes, while introducing new RISC-based computers that competed directly with its existing CISC midrange systems.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Sun's move to SPARC was based on its decision to, instead of relying on improvements to CISC, transition to RISC as fast as possible.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The DEC engineers who designed DECstation with MIPS R2000 and not their company's own VAX did so because, they wrote, the former offered "at least a two-to-one performance advantage" for the cost.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] By the later 1980s, new RISC designs were easily outperforming all CISC designs by a wide margin.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] By 1992 Sun, DEC, HP, and IBM were the leading commercial RISC companies.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Other vendors began their own RISC efforts.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Among the available architectures were the DEC Alpha, AMD Am29000, Intel i860 and i960, Motorola 88000, IBM POWER, and, slightly later, the IBM/Apple/Motorola PowerPC.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Many of these have since disappeared due to them often offering no competitive advantage over others of the same era.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Those that remain are often used only in niche markets or as parts of other systems; of the designs from these traditional vendors, only SPARC and the PowerPC-derived Power ISA have any significant remaining market.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] With the rise in mobile, automotive, streaming, smart device computing, ARM became the most widely used ISA, the company estimating that almost half of all CPUs shipped in history have been ARM.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] A common misunderstanding of the phrase "reduced instruction set computer" is that instructions are simply eliminated, resulting in a smaller set of instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In fact, over the years, RISC instruction sets have grown in size, and today many of them have a larger set of instructions than many CISC CPUs.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Some RISC processors such as the PowerPC have instruction sets as large as the CISC IBM System/370, for example; conversely, the DEC PDP-8—clearly a CISC CPU because many of its instructions involve multiple memory accesses—has only 8 basic instructions and a few extended instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The term *load–store architecture* is sometimes preferred.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Another way of looking at the RISC/CISC debate is to consider what is exposed to the compiler.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In a CISC processor, the hardware may internally use registers and flag bits in order to implement a single complex instruction such as `STRING MOVE`, but hide those details from the compiler.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The internal operations of a RISC processor are "exposed to the compiler", leading to the backronym 'Relegate Interesting Stuff to the Compiler'.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Most RISC architectures have fixed-length instructions and a simple encoding, which simplifies fetch, decode, and issue logic considerably.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This is among the main goals of the RISC approach.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Some of this is possible only due to the contemporary move to 32-bit formats.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] For instance, in a typical program, over 30% of all the numeric constants are either 0 or 1, 95% will fit in one byte, and 99% in a 16-bit value.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] When computers were based on 8- or 16-bit words, it would be difficult to have an immediate combined with the opcode in a single memory word, although certain instructions like increment and decrement did this implicitly by using a different opcode.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In contrast, a 32-bit machine has ample room to encode an immediate value, and doing so avoids the need to do a second memory read to pick up the value.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This is why many RISC processors allow a 12- or 13-bit constant to be encoded directly into the instruction word.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Assuming a 13-bit constant area, as is the case in the MIPS and RISC designs, another 19 bits are available for the instruction encoding.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This leaves ample room to indicate both the opcode and one or two registers.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Register-to-register operations, mostly math and logic, require enough bits to encode the two or three registers being used.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Most processors use the three-operand format `A = B + C`, in which case three register numbers are needed.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] If the processor has 32 registers, each one requires a 5-bit number for 15 bits total.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] If one of these registers is replaced by an immediate, there is still room to encode the two remaining registers and the opcode.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Common instructions found in multi-word systems, like `INC` and `DEC`, which reduce the number of words that have to be read before performing the instruction, are unnecessary in RISC as they can be accomplished with a single register and the immediate value 1.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The original RISC-I format remains a canonical example of the concept.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] It uses 7 bits for the opcode and a 1-bit flag for conditional codes, the following 5 bits for the destination register, and the next five for the first operand.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This leaves 14 bits, the first of which indicates whether the following 13 contain an immediate value or uses only five of them to indicate a register for the second operand.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] A more complex example is the MIPS encoding, which uses only 6 bits for the opcode, followed by two 5-bit registers.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The remaining 16 bits could be used in two ways: one as a 16-bit immediate value, or as a 5-bit shift value (used only in shift operations, otherwise zero) and the remaining 6 bits as an extension on the opcode.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In the case of register-to-register arithmetic operations, the opcode was 0 and the last 6 bits contained the actual code; those that used an immediate value used the normal opcode field at the front.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] One drawback of 32-bit instructions is reduced code density, which is a more adverse characteristic in embedded computing than it is in the workstation and server markets that RISC architectures were originally designed to serve.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] To address this problem, several architectures, such as SuperH (1992), ARM thumb (1994), MIPS16e (2004), Power Variable Length Encoding ISA (2006), RISC-V, and the Adapteva Epiphany, have an optional short, feature-reduced compressed instruction set.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Generally, these instructions expose a smaller number of registers and fewer bits for immediate values, and often use a two-operand format to eliminate one register number from instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] A two-operand format in a system with 16 registers requires 8 bits for register numbers, leaving another 8 for an opcode or other uses.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The SH5 also follows this pattern, albeit having evolved in the opposite direction, having added longer 32-bit instructions to an original 16-bit encoding.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The most characteristic aspect of RISC is executing at least one instruction per cycle.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Single-cycle operation is described as "the rapid execution of simple functions that dominate a computer's instruction stream", thus seeking to deliver an average throughput approaching one instruction per cycle for any single instruction stream.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Many early RISC designs also shared the characteristic of having a branch delay slot, an instruction space immediately following a jump or branch.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The instruction in this space is executed, whether or not the branch is taken (in other words, the effect of the branch is delayed).
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This instruction keeps the ALU of the CPU busy for the extra time normally needed to perform a branch.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Nowadays, the branch delay slot is considered an unfortunate side effect of a particular strategy for implementing some RISC designs, and modern RISC designs generally do away with it (such as PowerPC and more recent versions of SPARC and MIPS).
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] It was argued that such functions would be better performed by sequences of simpler instructions if this could yield implementations small enough to leave room for many registers, reducing the number of slow memory accesses.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In these simple designs, most instructions are of uniform length and similar structure, arithmetic operations are restricted to CPU registers and only separate *load* and *store* instructions access memory.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] These properties enable a better balancing of pipeline stages than before, making RISC pipelines significantly more efficient and allowing higher clock frequencies.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Yet another impetus of both RISC and other designs came from practical measurements on real-world programs.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Andrew Tanenbaum summed up many of these, demonstrating that processors often had oversized immediates.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] For instance, he showed that 98% of all the constants in a program would fit in 13 bits, yet many CPU designs dedicated 16 or 32 bits to store them.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This suggests that, to reduce the number of memory accesses, a fixed-length machine could store constants in unused bits of the instruction word itself, so that they would be immediately ready when the CPU needs them (much like immediate addressing in a conventional design).
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This required small opcodes in order to leave room for a reasonably sized constant in a 32-bit instruction word.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Since many real-world programs spend most of their time executing simple operations, some researchers decided to focus on making those operations as fast as possible.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The clock rate of a CPU is limited by the time it takes to execute the slowest *sub-operation* of any instruction; decreasing that cycle-time often accelerates the execution of other instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The focus on "reduced instructions" led to the resulting machine being called a "reduced instruction set computer" (RISC).
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The goal was to make instructions so simple that they could *easily* be pipelined, in order to achieve a *single clock* throughput at *high frequencies*.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This contrasted with CISC designs whose "crucial arithmetic operations and register transfers" were considered difficult to pipeline.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Later, it was noted that one of the most significant characteristics of RISC processors was that external memory was only accessible by a *load* or *store* instruction.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] All other instructions were limited to internal registers.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This simplified many aspects of processor design: allowing instructions to be fixed-length, simplifying pipelines, and isolating the logic for dealing with the delay in completing a memory access (cache miss, etc.) to only two instructions.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This led to RISC designs being referred to as *load–store* architectures.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Some CPUs have been specifically designed to have a very small set of instructions—but these designs are very different from classic RISC designs, so they have been given other names such as minimal instruction set computer (MISC) or transport triggered architecture (TTA).
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] RISC architectures have traditionally had few successes in the desktop PC and commodity server markets, where the x86-based platforms remain the dominant processor architecture.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] However, this may change, as ARM-based processors are being developed for higher-performance systems.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Manufacturers including Cavium, AMD, and Qualcomm have released server processors based on the ARM architecture.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] ARM further partnered with Cray in 2017 to produce an ARM-based supercomputer.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] On the desktop, Microsoft announced that it planned to support the PC version of Windows 10 on Qualcomm Snapdragon-based devices in 2017 as part of its partnership with Qualcomm.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] These devices will support Windows applications compiled for 32-bit x86 via an x86 processor emulator that translates 32-bit x86 code to ARM64 code.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Apple announced they will transition their Mac desktop and laptop computers from Intel processors to internally developed ARM64-based SoCs called Apple silicon; the first such computers, using the Apple M1 processor, were released in November 2020.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Macs with Apple silicon can run x86-64 binaries with Rosetta 2, an x86-64 to ARM64 translator.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Outside of the desktop arena, however, the ARM RISC architecture is in widespread use in smartphones, tablets and many forms of embedded devices.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] While early RISC designs differed significantly from contemporary CISC designs, by 2000 the highest-performing CPUs in the RISC line were almost indistinguishable from the highest-performing CPUs in the CISC line.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] RISC architectures are now used across a range of platforms, from smartphones and tablet computers to some of the world's fastest supercomputers such as Fugaku, the fastest on the TOP500 list as of November 2020, and Summit, Sierra, and Sunway TaihuLight, the next three on that list.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] By the beginning of the 21st century, the majority of low-end and mobile systems relied on RISC architectures.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] RISC architectures have become popular in open source processors and soft microprocessors since they are relatively simple to implement, which makes them suitable for FPGA implementations and prototyping, for instance.
[src:mips-assembly/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Wilson were awarded the Charles Stark Draper Prize by the United States National Academy of Engineering for their contributions to the invention, development, and implementation of reduced instruction set computer (RISC) chips.
